#!/usr/bin/env bash
# fedora-bootstrap — orchestrator. Run as ROOT on a fresh host (Day 0).
# Version: 1.2.38 (docs-access-honesty: correct two false public-exposure claims in README. The Access table marked dev-container ssh/mosh as public=no and the prose claimed the public IP exposes exactly two surfaces, but this host deploys the fedora-dev Quadlet which publishes public key-only ssh:4444 + mosh 61001-62000/udp; the table cell + sentence now list the dev container's key-only public door as a third hardened surface, native RDP/VNC + Cockpit remaining tailnet-only. Found during the SSH/Mosh connectivity audit. Docs only; no host package/service/deploy-path change. Prior: v1.2.37 (assemble-policy-order: FIX the v1.2.35 ordering bug. setup-user.sh built the claudebox in user 3/5 BEFORE writing the image-trust policy.json in user 4/5, so on an ALREADY-DEPLOYED host whose restrictive policy lacks the toolbox scope, the assemble's quay.io/fedora/fedora-toolbox pull was rejected before user 4/5 could add it - every setup.sh re-run failed at user 3/5 with `Source image ... is rejected by policy`. A small idempotent guard now trusts the toolbox base in the live policy.json BEFORE the assemble - a no-op on a fresh host with no policy yet and when the scope is already present. v1.2.35 only fixed FRESH day-zero hosts; this fixes the re-run-on-deployed-host path. Host-only. VALIDATION HONESTY: bash -n clean + guard-logic simulation only - NOT run on a live host; a real setup.sh re-run on a deployed host is the sole end-to-end proof. Prior: v1.2.36 (release-no-tag: drop the per-release git-tag mandate from the release convention - it adds no value for this single-operator, deploy-from-main fleet and was already abandoned after v1.2.19 while the version reached 1.2.35. The host deploys main not tags, rollback is `git checkout <commit>` + re-run setup.sh, nothing external pins a release, and the version-of-record is already in-tree triplicate: VERSION + this setup.sh header + the README front-matter, plus the README Upgrading changelog. RELEASING + RELEASE-DOC CONVENTION in CLAUDE.md and the agent-law policy/CLAUDE.md drop the tag step + the immutable-tags rule; the stale step 5 `git push origin main` is corrected to the PR-merge model. Tagging stays OPTIONAL for a deliberate milestone. Control-plane class (touches policy/CLAUDE.md): kept STANDALONE + FLAGGED in the merge TLDR for Arthur's scrutiny, merged on the same single clickable APPROVE - there is no control-plane-approved label and no CI diff-guard (those server-side layers were dropped fleet-wide; the in-session click is the sole gate). Docs/process only; no host package/service/deploy-path change. Prior: v1.2.35 (toolbox-trust: fix - claudebox-rebuild on the host failed `Source image quay.io/fedora/fedora-toolbox:44 is rejected by policy` (exit 125) after the first build. The image-trust policy.json default-rejects, trusting only ghcr.io/oso-gato + registry.fedoraproject.org/fedora + containers-storage - NOT quay.io/fedora/fedora-toolbox, the claudebox base pinned in distrobox.ini that distrobox re-pulls on every rebuild. The first day-zero assemble runs in setup-user.sh phase 3 BEFORE the policy.json is written in phase 4, so it pulls the toolbox under the permissive default and caches it; only SUBSEQUENT rebuilds re-pull under the now-restrictive policy and are rejected - which is why the first build always works and updates fail. setup-user.sh now trusts the toolbox base in BOTH the create-heredoc for fresh hosts AND the idempotent python merge, so re-running setup.sh repairs an already-deployed host like erebus in place. Same insecureAcceptAnything posture as the fedora base, upgradeable to sigstoreSigned in lockstep. Host-only - no package/service/deploy-path change; fedora-dev + fedora-desktop are unaffected, they run no restrictive policy. Prior: v1.2.34 (throwaway-churn-harden: harden the host pre-merge throwaway-BUILD mechanism for churn — the host top-level engine is NOT chroot-isolated, so it can use BOTH a writable bind cache AND the podman layer cache. (1) PERSISTENT DNF PACKAGE CACHE: build-candidate.sh binds $HOME/.cache/fd-dnf (FD_DNF_CACHE, created if missing) onto the candidate build's /var/cache/libdnf5:rw so the RPMs a candidate downloads PERSIST across ALL later candidate builds — a forced re-run serves them from disk instead of re-downloading (measured 94s->33s on a forced in-box re-run). The disposable localhost/disposable/<name>:val-<sha> tag + EXIT-trap rmi + no --no-cache are UNCHANGED; the layer cache still survives the candidate rmi, so the dnf bind cache is additive (even a layer that re-runs dnf serves RPMs from disk). (2) ORPHAN SWEEPER: NEW throwaway-sweep.sh, invoked at live-gate-watch.sh start (self-throttled to once per FD_SWEEP_INTERVAL_MIN, default 30m, so calling it every 15s poll is ~free; also wirable to a periodic systemd --user timer/cron, see the README note), removes AGED (older than FD_SWEEP_AGE_MIN, default 120m) orphan localhost/disposable/* images + vcand-* containers + throwaway source trees (now created under $FD_THROWAWAY_TMPDIR=$HOME/.cache/fd-throwaway by build-candidate.sh + live-gate-run.sh so they are findable) that a kill -9/OOM/crash left behind — the per-run EXIT traps in build-candidate.sh + validate-candidate.sh only fire on a CLEAN exit. SAFE: age-gated (a live gate's current artifacts are ~1-3min old, far younger than the window), non-forced podman rmi (an image still referenced by a running container is skipped), vcand-* only (never a real workload), flock-guarded. (3) BOUNDED CACHE-GC in the same reaper caps both persistent caches so churn can't exhaust the VPS quota: the dnf cache to FD_DNF_CACHE_CAP_GB (default 5, keeps newest RPMs + prunes oldest over the cap) + a `podman image prune` of DANGLING build-cache layers older than FD_BUILDCACHE_AGE (default 168h; dangling-only so tagged ghcr.io/oso-gato images are never touched). All caps are overridable env vars with sane defaults. setup-user.sh installs throwaway-sweep.sh alongside build/validate-candidate.sh. Host-only validation tooling; no host package/service or production deploy-path change. Prior: v1.2.33 (live-gate-harden: the host live-gate now consumes a labelled PR's in-repo .live-gate SAFELY and enforces loopback-only fences, completing the Model C dynamic-discovery work that landed on this branch. (1) [HOST RCE FIX] live-gate-run.sh replaced `set -a; . "$PRESET"; set +a` — which EXECUTED an untrusted PR's .live-gate as host shell at source-time, so FENCE_x="$(cmd)" or `KEY=1; cmd` ran arbitrary code ON THE HOST — with a parse-not-source consumer (lg_load): each KEY=VALUE is read line by line, the key is checked against the live-gate schema allowlist (a contract can't clobber PATH/IFS/...), one layer of surrounding quotes is stripped, and the value is assigned via `printf -v` (never eval, never `.`). Safe subset: single-quoted values are VERBATIM (their $()/&&/;/</> are inert here and run only LATER, inside the fenced disposable container via --health-cmd/podman exec); double-quoted values unescape only \" \$ \\ \` (no $VAR expansion) and REFUSE command substitution/backticks; unquoted values must be a single bare token. A hostile/malformed contract is rejected with a RED verdict (loud, never a silent skip) and is NOT executed. (2) [loopback-only enforcement] validate-candidate.sh fails closed (RED) if the resolved per-target fence carries a publish flag (-p/--publish/-P/--publish-all, incl. =forms and the no-space -p8443:8443) BEFORE launching the disposable container — the gate probes the candidate on its OWN loopback via podman exec, so no port may be published. (3) Model C dynamic discovery (already on this branch): org-wide live-validate label discovery, in-repo .live-gate contract, clone-on-demand, structural guard, multi-target builds. fedora-desktop.env is normalized to the parser grammar (one KEY=VALUE per line, cross-references inlined, HEALTH/PROBE single-quoted); fedora-dev.env is unchanged; the sample + handoff docs are corrected from "sourced" to "parsed, not sourced". Host-only validation tooling; no production deploy-path change. Prior: v1.2.32 (tmux-coview-docs: the v1.2.31 multi-device tmux session behaviour is now documented fleet-wide. README.md gains a 'Multi-device sessions / tmux geometry' section and its stale per-LOGIN_KEY tmux bullet is corrected to the actual single shared `main` group; FLEET.md 'Shared invariants' gains a 'Multi-device terminal' bullet identical in all three boxes; BUILD PRINCIPLES VALIDATE gains an empirical-validation clause — prove terminal/TUI rendering with a REAL multi-client PTY harness and assert the bytes each client renders, since a naive byte VT model mis-reads UTF-8 fills like `·` as garbage. DOCS ONLY: no setup behaviour change; the runtime tmux.conf shipped in v1.2.31. Prior: v1.2.31 (tmux-latest-coview: the system /etc/tmux.conf now defaults to window-size=latest so the shared "main" session follows whichever device most recently sent INPUT — seamless macOS<->iPad handoff over mosh: type on the Mac and the whole session is Mac-sized, pick up the iPad and type and it rescales to the iPad; the idle device stays mosh-connected and blank-letterboxes/crops cleanly, reclaiming full size on its next keystroke; when the active device disconnects the session falls back to whoever remains. Adds `setw -g fill-character ' '` so an idle LARGER device's surplus area is BLANK rather than the garble-looking `·` middle-dot fill (tmux's compiled default), and `prefix+g` to cycle latest -> smallest (every device sees the WHOLE session sized to the smallest connected client, big screens blank-letterbox) -> largest (biggest connected screen wins, smaller devices crop) -> latest. Root cause proven against tmux 3.6 source + a live multi-client geometry harness: a tmux window has exactly ONE size shared by all co-viewing clients, so differently-sized devices on the SAME tab cannot each render full-size — unfixable in tmux (one program = one pty = one cell grid); `latest` makes the active device win and the mismatched device degrade cleanly (crop/letterbox, never stale garbage — the surplus is actively redrawn each frame). Supersedes the v1.2.18 `window-size=smallest` choice, which fit the shared window to the SMALLEST client and let the `·` fill on larger screens read as 'completely garbled'. setup-host.sh re-stamp only; no operator data migration. Prior: v1.2.30 (rebuild-backstop: lower the claudebox box-rebuild crash/hang backstop on claudebox-rebuild-run.service from TimeoutStartSec=900 (15min) to 480 (8min). A practical exam on this VPS measured the box dnf install at 101s, a full rebuild ~150s, and the worst-case LEGIT rebuild (cold 2.17GB image pull + first-enter retries) ~400-450s, so 900s was ~2x the worst case and let a genuinely-stuck rebuild lock out new sessions for 15min. 480s clears the worst-case legit rebuild with margin while halving crash recovery; it only ever fires on a STUCK rebuild (a healthy one is detected complete within ~2s, so normal rebuilds are never clipped). Host-only change: the host serializes the rebuild via systemd, so the fd-9 box-rebuild.lock leak that hangs the workload boxes does NOT apply here - the matching workload fix ships in fedora-dev/fedora-desktop. No other change. Prior: v1.2.29 (live-gate-cadence: the live-gate watcher now polls every 15s (was 5min) for snappy turn-around during active development — live-gate-watch.timer OnBootSec/OnUnitActiveSec=15s + AccuracySec=1s (REQUIRED for systemd to honor a sub-minute interval; default accuracy batches to ~1min) + the RandomizedDelaySec jitter dropped. Safe at 15s: the watcher self-serializes via flock, so while a build runs the intervening firings skip instantly; an idle firing is a cheap distrobox-enter + one `gh pr list` (well under rate limits). The build+gate (~90s+) dominates total turn, so 15s is mostly pickup latency. No other change. Prior: v1.2.28 (live-gate-fix: two robustness fixes to the v1.2.27 transport, both PROVEN. (1) The watcher runs IN the claudebox: live-gate-watch.service ExecStart now `distrobox enter claudebox -- bash -lc ...` because gh + git are CLAUDEBOX tools, NOT on the minimal host — the watcher polls gh + drives the host podman engine via the box's CONTAINER_HOST bridge (build/run still land on the HOST engine). Without this the host systemd --user service failed `gh pr list` (no gh on host) and gated nothing. (2) Setup's workload-clone update no longer ABORTS on a dirty working tree: ~/<name> is a SETUP-MANAGED clone (the loop tooling fetches PR refs + git-archives, never authoritatively edits it), so the update now discards stray working-tree changes (git reset --hard HEAD + git clean -fd) then `git merge --ff-only origin/main` — preserving the force-push detection the old `git pull --ff-only` had (a blind `reset --hard origin/main` would SILENTLY accept a force-push to main; this still surfaces it). Prior: v1.2.27 (live-gate-loop: closes the pre-merge autonomous-loop TRANSPORT. Adds live-gate-run.sh (gate ONE PR: build the candidate disposably via build-candidate.sh -> validate-candidate.sh Gate B -> `gh pr comment` the GREEN/RED verdict; the host COMMENTS, never merges) + live-gate-watch.sh (a systemd --user timer that polls `live-validate`-labelled workload PRs, dedups per-commit via ~/.local/state/live-gate/<wl>-<sha>.done, invokes the runner) + per-workload presets (live-gate-presets/<wl>.env -> ~/.config/live-gate/; host fallback, a workload may ship its own `.live-gate`). The gate runs a DISPOSABLE container that never touches the running workload, so it is NOT gated on the dev session — validation runs WHILE fedora-dev is in active use (the loop's whole point). PROVEN end-to-end: a `live-validate`-labelled fedora-dev test PR was built-from-source + gated GREEN on the host and the verdict posted back to the PR; the watcher discovered the labelled PR and deduped. Closes the loop: fedora-dev opens/labels a PR -> host builds+gates+verdicts -> fedora-dev iterates (RED) or Arthur merges (GREEN), human at exactly one point. setup-user.sh installs the two scripts + presets + units and enables live-gate-watch.timer. Prior: v1.2.26 (live-gate-builder: adds build-candidate.sh — the host's pre-merge BUILD step, the linchpin of the live-gate loop. Given a workload clone + an optional PR ref, it exports the ref to a THROWAWAY source tree (git archive -> mktemp, no clone mutation), podman builds a DISPOSABLE candidate (localhost/disposable/<name>:val-<sha>; default isolation works on the host's native-overlay top-level engine — no --isolation=chroot, unlike the nested dev box), hands the local image to validate-candidate.sh (Gate B: --rm fenced run + access-probe), then rmi's the candidate (base layers stay cached for the next churn). PROVEN end-to-end: the host built fedora-dev from source + gated it GREEN — the pre-merge build->gate path that CI (no PR publish) and the dev box (cannot live-run PID-1) cannot do. setup-user.sh now installs build-candidate.sh AND validate-candidate.sh (the latter was previously an uninstalled orphan). Sanctioned by the v1.2.25 carve-out: never pushed, never a WORKLOAD_CONTAINERS member, never in the deploy path. Prior: v1.2.25 (policy-carveout: amends the host law to PERMIT disposable host validation builds. policy/CLAUDE.md (+ project CLAUDE.md) now split "build a SHIPPING image" (always CI, never on the host) from "build a THROWAWAY validation image" (PERMITTED, pre-merge live-gate only): the host MAY podman build a candidate SOLELY to live-test an open PR before merge — required because CI publishes nothing pullable on an open PR (build.yml push:false on pull_request) and the dev box's nested engine cannot live-run a PID-1 image, so the host is the ONLY surface that yields a faithful pre-merge verdict. Permitted ONLY when localhost/disposable-namespaced (never a ghcr deploy ref), never podman push'd (the host holds no write:packages credential), run --rm + rmi'd on teardown, and never a WORKLOAD_CONTAINERS member. This is exactly what validation/rollback-spike.sh already does — the flat "never podman build" law had silently forbidden it. Shipping images stay CI-only + cosign-signed; the deploy path is UNCHANGED. Enables the pre-merge live-gate loop (the host candidate-builder is the next, non-control-plane step). Prior: v1.2.24 (default-effort: the host claudebox now STARTS every session at maximum effort. The `claude` wrapper (setup-user.sh) injects --settings {"ultracode":true} so each session begins in ultracode (= xhigh effort + workflow-by-default); ultracode is SESSION-SCOPED and IGNORED in settings files, so the wrapper is the only place it can be made a default. policy/managed-settings.json also gains top-level "effortLevel":"xhigh" as the persistent floor for any non-wrapper path (subagents, direct /usr/bin/claude). With v1.2.20's defaultMode:auto this COMPLETES the autonomous-defaults set: a fresh setup.sh re-run brings the box up in auto mode at ultracode with no per-session action. MERGE GATE UNCHANGED — the gate-push.sh ask hook, the git push / gh pr merge deny rules, and disableBypassPermissionsMode all remain. Prior: v1.2.23 loop-gate-B: parameterized validate-candidate.sh (the pre-merge LIVE gate) with CAND_FENCE (the candidate's run-contract caps/devices, minus public ports + real secrets; default = hardest untrusted fence) + CAND_PROBE (the workload's "does it serve" assertion, run on the candidate's OWN loopback via podman exec). Proven faithful: a correctly-serving candidate PASSES; a candidate that is healthy/up but serves wrong (HTTP 500) is caught by the probe and FAILS — the access-path probe is load-bearing, not just the healthcheck. Validation tooling; no production behavior change. Prior: v1.2.22 loop-gate-A: proved container-refresh.sh's never-fired ROLLBACK branch GREEN via validation/rollback-spike.sh — a bad :latest that won't go healthy is retagged to the prior digest, restarted, and recovers with a .rolled-back marker. Two fixes it required: an explicit HealthCmd in the spike's throwaway Quadlet (OCI drops a built image's HEALTHCHECK) + a new BUSY_PROBE seam in container-refresh.sh (UNSET in production = the claudebox probe unchanged; a non-claudebox workload sets BUSY_PROBE=/bin/true, the documented empty-probe path). No production behavior change. Prior: v1.2.21 policy-fix: setup-user.sh wrote the image-trust policy.json "containers-storage" transport as a bare ARRAY instead of a scope->requirements OBJECT; containers-image rejected the WHOLE policy ("JSON object expected, got 91") so EVERY ghcr.io/oso-gato pull failed and no workload could start (fedora-dev stuck restart-looping). Fixed both writers (create-heredoc + merge), the idempotent merge now REPAIRS an already-broken host in place, and a fail-closed structural check rejects any non-object transport. Prior: v1.2.20 auto-mode: the host claudebox now DEFAULTS to the 'auto' permission mode — policy/managed-settings.json drops "disableAutoMode":"disable" and adds "defaultMode":"auto", so in-box sessions start without routine permission prompts (a background classifier still vets each action). The MERGE GATE IS UNCHANGED: the managed gate-push.sh 'ask' hook, the git push / gh pr merge deny rules, and disableBypassPermissionsMode all remain, so nothing reaches main without explicit approval. Prior: v1.2.19 policy: the host image-trust policy.json now also permits the class-(a) Fedora base registry.fedoraproject.org/fedora plus the containers-storage transport (local save/load), so the validation/ host-validation spikes+gates can pull stock Fedora fixtures into a throwaway tar cache. Production run-set UNCHANGED — workload Quadlets reference only ghcr.io/oso-gato/*, default stays reject, the docker "" fallback stays reject; this widens only what may be PULLED for disposable host-validation, not what RUNS. setup-user.sh writes it fresh (heredoc) and idempotently/additively merges the two entries into an existing policy.json without clobbering operator edits. Same insecureAcceptAnything posture as the oso-gato stanza; both upgradeable to sigstoreSigned in lockstep later. Prior: v1.2.18 tmux SINGLE-GROUP multi-client geometry-race fix; v1.2.17 FLEET.md swarm map; v1.2.16 Day-0 wizard (day0.sh asks for the TS auth key); v1.2.15 spin-up path explicit; v1.2.14 day-0 TS_AUTHKEY prompt; v1.2.13 docs cleanup; v1.2.12 FLEET governance (3-box model, host PR-only, fedora-dev sole merge box); v1.2.11 BUILT promotion gate; v1.2.10 HEADLESS prerequisite; v1.2.9 Principle 3 MINIMAL; v1.2.8 Principle 2(c); v1.2.7 PR-first maintainership; v1.2.5 verify.sh fail2ban euid-gate fix; v1.2.4 genesis/mother-platform role + fedora-dev maintainership.))))))))))
#
# Runs the two privilege layers in their correct identities (see README "Privilege layers"):
#   setup-host.sh  — the SYSTEM layer, as ROOT: host packages, /etc, system services, the
#                    tailnet node, and CREATES the operating user + its rootless prerequisites.
#   setup-user.sh  — the ROOTLESS layer, as the operating user: user podman socket, ssh keys,
#                    claudebox, Claude policy, verify. Needs NO host privilege.
# Idempotent — re-run safely.
set -euo pipefail
HERE="$(cd "$(dirname "$0")" && pwd)"
U="${BOOTSTRAP_USER:-core}"

if [ "$(id -u)" = 0 ]; then
    BOOTSTRAP_USER="$U" "$HERE/setup-host.sh"
    # Hand off to the operating user for the rootless layer. The root phase already
    # brought up its user bus, so `su -` finds it. `< /dev/null` keeps a queued paste line
    # (e.g. a following `passwd`) from being swallowed by a child that reads stdin.
    su - "$U" -c "GH_KEYS_USER='${GH_KEYS_USER:-oso-gato}' '$HERE/setup-user.sh'" < /dev/null
else
    # Invoked as the unprivileged user: run ONLY the rootless layer. The system layer must
    # already have been provisioned as root (run setup.sh as root on a fresh host).
    echo ">> Running the rootless (user) layer only. The SYSTEM layer must already be in place;"
    echo ">> on a fresh host run setup.sh as root instead."
    exec "$HERE/setup-user.sh"
fi
